'''Sawi''', '''Savi''', or '''Sauji''',<ref>''Sauji'' is the [[endonym]] reported in {{harvtxt|Liljegren|2009|p=10}}</ref> is an endangered{{sfn|Bashir|2016b|pp=640–41}} [[Indo-Aryan language]] of northeastern [[Afghanistan]]. It is classified as a member of the [[Shina language|Shina]] language cluster within the [[Dardic languages|Dardic]] subgroup.

It is spoken in the village of [[Sau, Kunar|Sau]], on the east bank of the [[Kunar River]], around {{convert|20|km}} south of the town of [[Arandu, Pakistan|Arandu]], which is on the border with Pakistan's [[Chitral region]].{{sfn|Liljegren|2009|p=10}}
Sawi speakers consider themselves part of the Gawar ethnic group, which is found in half a dozen of the surrounding villages and whose language is [[Gawarbati language|Gawarbati]]. In communicating with them, the people of Sau reportedly resort to using [[Pashto]].{{sfn|Cacopardo|Cacopardo|2001|pp=96, 231–32}}
During the long period of unrest, the population of the village was displaced into refugee camps in Chitral and [[Dir, Pakistan|Dir]], but reportedly many people have now returned to Afghanistan.{{sfn|Liljegren|2009|p=10}}

== History ==
The closest relative of the Sawi language is the southern variety of [[Palula]] spoken in [[Ashret]] further up the Kunar Valley in Chitral. Many Sawi speakers are aware of the similarity between the two languages, and some consider the people of Ashret as their "brothers".{{sfn|Liljegren|2009|pp=11, 55}} Henrik Liljegren's study of the shared linguistic features and the local oral traditions suggest that the ancestors of these language communities are likely to have migrated from the present-day [[Diamer District]] on the Indus River. There was probably an early split between Northern and Southern Palula, with Sawi subsequently branching off from the latter.{{sfn|Liljegren|2009|ps =; see particularly pp. 54–58}} The current similarity between the two varieties of Palula is then explained as a result of convergence.

== Grammar ==
The presence of weak voiced aspirates (bh, dh, gh) was cautiously reported by Buddruss in 1967,{{sfn|Buddruss|1967|p=22}} but {{harvtxt|Liljegren|2009|p=31}} found them to be absent from the speech of his consultant(s). It is likely that the loss of aspiration in the ancestor language could have been related to the development of a tone system.<ref>{{harvnb|Liljegren|2009|pp=34–35, 41}}. Cf. the analysis of Kolkati in {{harvnb|Liljegren|2013|pp=143–44}}</ref>

Possibly under the influence of Gawarbati,{{sfn|Liljegren|2009|pp=40–41}} Sawi has developed a [[voiceless lateral fricative]] ''{{IPA|ɬ}}'' out of the ''*tr'' consonant clusters of the earlier language, compare for example Sawi ''ɬo'' with Southern Palula ''tróo'' 'three'.{{sfn|Liljegren|2009|pp=34, 36}}

Unlike the main Shina varieties, where the past and present [[Grammatical tense|tense]] are typically marked for [[Grammatical person|person]], Sawi and Palula verb tenses are almost entirely [[participle]]-based, with only traces of [[Grammatical agreement|agreement]] for person.{{sfn|Liljegren|2013|p=153}}
Like [[Torwali language|Torwali]], Sawi has [[grammaticalise]]d the category of [[Animacy (linguistics)|animacy]] in its [[Nominal (linguistics)|nominal]] morphology.{{sfn|Bashir|2016a|at = p. 266, n. 33. This contrasts for example with [[Kalasha language|Kalasha]], [[Khowar]], [[Shumashti]] and [[Pashai]] where animacy has been grammaticalised in the ''verbal'' morphology.}}
The [[Agent (grammar)|agent]] suffix is ''-e'' for [[perfective]] transitive verbs. Unlike the main Shina varieties, Sawi does not seem to possess an agent suffix for imperfective transitive verbs.{{sfn|Schmidt|Kaul|2008|p=249}}

